Package refactor

Class GlobalSettings

  • java.lang.Object
    • refactor.GlobalSettings
  • public class GlobalSettings
extends java.lang.Object
    This interface just stores important settings that are used throughout the whole protocol implementation It serves as a kind of utility to avoid inconsistencies
    Since:
    20.06.2019
    Version:
    1.0
    Author:
    Filipe Medeiros - filipesilvamedeiros@gmail.com, Filipe Medeiros - github.com/filipesmedeiros

    • Field Detail

      • LOCAL_ADDRESS

        private static java.net.InetSocketAddress LOCAL_ADDRESS
        This field stores the local address of the local node, so it can be accessed throughout the whole program. It can be set and got at will, but is assumed to only be set once, at the beginning of execution. It is assumed also to be an address that all Nodes can see and connect to

      • SETTINGS_LOCKED

        private static boolean SETTINGS_LOCKED
        This field if used as a flag representing that the execution of the protocol in this Node has started, so some setting cannot be changed

      • CONNECT_TIMEOUT

        public static int CONNECT_TIMEOUT
        Maximum time, in milliseconds, a thread can block in order to try to connect a node to another one. After this time, an exception will be thrown and the connection between the nodes will be assumed to have failed. Changing this setting mid-execution is permitted but discouraged and can lead to incorrect behaviors and errors

      • FLEX_THREAD_POOL

        public static final java.util.concurrent.ExecutorService FLEX_THREAD_POOL
        This is the first global Thread pool of the program. It is responsible for flexible tasks, such as sending pings with Oracles and such tasks. It seems logical to have the whole implementation use the same Thread pools but this can be changed in the future, if needed

      • FIXED_THREAD_POOL

        public static final java.util.concurrent.ExecutorService FIXED_THREAD_POOL
        This is the second global Thread pool. It is responsible for the few fixed Threads the program has, like the Threads of the TCP layer (receiving and sending), etc. The number of Threads is fixed and depends on the implementation

      • TIMER

        public static final java.util.Timer TIMER
        This is the single Timer used to manage all the periodic tasks the protocol has to execute. To use it, the program adds TimerTasks to this timer. They should complete quickly, as to not block other tasks in the timer

      • CHARSET

        public static java.nio.charset.Charset CHARSET
        Keeps information on what the current implementation charset is, for encoding messages. Changing this setting mid-execution is permitted but discouraged and can lead to incorrect behaviors and errors

      • MAX_MESSAGE_SIZE

        public static int MAX_MESSAGE_SIZE
        Maximum size of a message, including metadata and data, in bytes. Messages can have metadata of varying lengths, and most of the time, they will either have a lot of metadata fields or a lot of data, but most likely never both, so having only a maximum size for the whole message seems to be the most practical solution, or else resources would be wasted. The protocol will read messages in blocks (at max) of this size. Changing this setting mid-execution is permitted but discouraged and can lead to incorrect behaviors and errors

      • MAX_LABEL_SIZE

        public static int MAX_LABEL_SIZE
        Maximum size of the labels of the entries of metadata, in bytes. This is to somewhat standardize serialization across implementations. Changing this setting mid-execution is permitted but discouraged

      • DEBUGGING_LEVEL

        public static byte DEBUGGING_LEVEL
        Define what level of debugging logs is wanted for each run of the program. 0 means no debug logs at all. 1 means only the most important (things that can break the system, but somehow are not caught by exceptions) 2 means all logs that can be potentially harmful, but may be OK 3 means all logs the program currently has
